el Stuart, along with lesser-known independents and activists such as Kent Mackenzie, Lynne Littman, and Jesús Salvador Treviño. While the former group reinvigorated a Cold War cultural liberalism, the latter group advocated for social justice in a city plagued by severe class stratification and racial segregation. Glick examines how mainstream and alternative filmmakers turned to the archives, civic institutions, and production facilities of Los Angeles in order to both change popular understandings of the city and shape the social consciousness of the nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDocumentary filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion picturesxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film / Genres / Documentary.2bisacsh  a1950s.  a1960s.  a1970s.  aactivists.  aamerican history.  abicentennial.  acold war.  acultural liberalism.  adavid wolper.  adocumentarians.  adocumentary film.  adocumentary.  ahollywood.  ajesus salvador trevino.  ajohn f kennedy.  ajournalism.  ajournalist.  akent mackenzie.  alos angeles.  alynne littman.  amel stuart.  aprimary source.  apublic history.  arace.  aracism.  asegregation.  asocial consciousness.  asocial justice.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066767708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUrban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019z97831106385160 cprintz978052029370040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520966918423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520966918/original  a978-3-11-063851-6  Urban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019c2016d2019  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018 